# Pre-deploy checks

Any time the user asks to **commit**, **push**, **deploy**, or otherwise ship code, run the relevant checks below **before** staging the commit. Do not skip.

## Rust changes (anything under `crates/`)

Run from the `crates/` directory before staging:

```sh
cargo check -p <crate>
```

If `cargo check` reports warnings or errors, fix them before committing — the codebase is warning-free and we keep it that way. For broader changes (multiple crates, workspace-level files), use `cargo check --workspace`. When tests are relevant to the change (e.g. anything in `api/`, `state.rs`, `can/`, or `types.rs`), also run `cargo test -p rudydae` and confirm 0 failures.

`cargo fmt` is enforced by the `scripts/git-hooks/pre-commit` hook (installed via `git config core.hooksPath scripts/git-hooks`); no need to run it by hand. CI also runs `cargo fmt --check`.

## SPA changes (anything under `link/`)

Run from the `link/` directory:

```sh
npm run typecheck
```

This runs `gen:routes && tsc -b --noEmit`. If it fails, fix the type errors before committing — never commit a broken `tsc -b`. Vitest only when the change touches code with existing test coverage.

## Both layers in one commit

If a commit touches both Rust and TypeScript (common for changes that affect wire types via `ts-rs`), run **both** sets of checks. The wire-type bindings are regenerated by `cargo test -p rudydae export_bindings`; if the Rust types changed and the regen is needed, do it before `npm run typecheck` so the SPA sees the new types.

## What "deploy" means here

- **commit + push to `main`** counts (we deploy from `main` via `deploy/pi5/rudy-update.sh`).
- Manual `scp` / `rsync` to the Pi counts.
- Anything that touches `config/rudyd.toml` or `deploy/pi5/*.service` definitely counts — config drift is the most common Pi outage cause.

## Reporting

When checks pass, summarize the result in the commit message section of the response (not the commit body itself), e.g.:

> Tests: 121 passed; 0 failed. fmt: clean. typecheck: clean.

If a check produces output worth keeping (e.g. `cargo test` summary lines), include the `test result:` lines so the user can see at a glance what was exercised.
